  <subsection xml:id="subsec-completing_the_square">
    <title>Completing the Square</title>
    <introduction>
      <p>
	In order to place a quadratic function into its vertex form, we will use the method of completing the square.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    
    <p>
      Remember that when we multiply two binomials, we must distribute.
      We can remember how to distribute using the mnemonic FOIL: <alert>F</alert>irst, <alert>O</alert>uter, <alert>I</alert>nner, <alert>L</alert>ast:
    </p>
    <figure>
      <caption>How to multiply binomials using the FOIL method.</caption>
      <image source="images/FOIL.png"/>
    </figure>
    <p>
      We can use this method to multiply a binomial by itself
      <md>
	<mrow>
	  (x + a)^2 \amp = (x + a)(x + a)
	</mrow>
	<mrow>\amp = xx + xa + ax + aa</mrow>
	<mrow>\amp = x^2 + ax + ax + a^2</mrow>
	<mrow>\amp = x^2 + 2ax + a^2.</mrow>
      </md>
      We call a quadratic function of the form <m>y = x^2 + 2ax + a^2</m> a <term>perfect square</term>.
      <idx>
	<h>Perfect Square</h>
      </idx>
    </p>

    <p>
      Given a quadratic equation <m>y = ax^2 + bx + c</m>, we can use the formula
      <me>(x + a)^2 = x^2 + 2ax + a^2 </me>
      to <term>complete the square</term>
      <idx>
	<h>Complete the Square</h>
      </idx>
      as follows.
      <algorithm xml:id="alg-completing_the_square">
	<title>Completing the Square</title>
	To place the quadratic function <m>y = ax^2 + bx + c</m> into vertex form, follow the steps.
	<ol>
	  <li>
	    Factor an <m>a</m> from the first two terms to get
	    <me>y = a\left(x^2 + \frac{b}{a}x\right) + c.</me>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    Add and subtract <m>\left(\frac{b}{2a}\right)^2</m> inside the parentheses to get
	    <me>
	      y = a\left(x^2 + \frac{b}{a}x + \left(\frac{b}{2a}\right)^2 - \left(\frac{b}{2a}\right)^2 \right) + c
	    </me>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    Factor the first three terms inside the parentheses as a perfect square
	    <me>y = a\left(\left(x + \frac{b}{2a}\right)^2 - \left(\frac{b}{2a}\right)^2 \right) + c</me>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    Distribute the <m>a</m> through the sum
	    <md>
	      <mrow>y \amp= a\left(x + \frac{b}{2a}\right)^2 - a\left(\frac{b}{2a}\right)^2 + c.</mrow>
	    </md>
	    The number
	    <m>h = -\frac{b}{2a}</m>
	    is the <m>x</m>-coordinate of the vertex and the number
	    <md>
	      <mrow>k \amp= - a\left(\frac{b}{2a}\right)^2 + c</mrow>
	      <mrow>\amp= -a\left(\frac{b^2}{4a^2}\right) + c</mrow>
	      <mrow>\amp= -\frac{b^2}{4a} + \frac{4ac}{4a}</mrow>
	      <mrow>\amp = - \frac{b^2 - 4ac}{4a}</mrow>
	    </md>
	    is the <m>y</m>-coordinate of the vertex.
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </algorithm>
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
	<p>
	  Find the vertex of the quadratic function <m>y = x^2 + 4x + 5</m>.
	</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
	<p>
	  When the coefficient on <m>x^2</m> is 1, we can skip the first step and the last step:
	</p>
	<md>
	  <mrow>y \amp = x^2 + 4x + 5 \amp\amp \text{Add and subtract}\ \left(\frac{4}{2}\right)^2 = 2^2</mrow>
	  <mrow>\amp= x^2 + 4x + 2^2 - 2^2 + 5 \amp\amp \text{Factor}</mrow>
	  <mrow>\amp = (x + 2)^2 - 2^2 + 5 \amp\amp \text{Simplify}</mrow>
	  <mrow>\amp = (x + 2)^2 - 4 + 5 \amp\amp \text{Simplify}</mrow>
	  <mrow>\amp = (x + 2)^2 + 1.</mrow>
	</md>
	<p>
	  The vertex of the quadratic function <m>y = x^2 + 4x + 5</m> is <m>(-2, 1)</m>.
	</p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
      <statement>
	<p>
	  Find the vertex of the quadratic function <m>y = 3x^2 - 4x + 5</m>.
	</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
	<p>
	  When the coefficient on <m>x</m> is a negative number, we can still use the formula by rewriting the subtraction as addition with a negative number.
	</p>
	<md>
	  <mrow>y \amp = 3x^2 - 4x + 5 \amp\amp \text{Rewrite}</mrow>
	  <mrow>\amp = 3x^2 + (-4)x + 5 \amp\amp \text{Factor}\ 3\ \text{from the first two terms}</mrow>
	  <mrow>\amp= 3\left(x^2 + \left(-\frac{4}{3}\right)x\right) + 5 \amp\amp \text{Add and subtract}\ \left(\frac{\frac{4}{3}}{2}\right)^2 = \left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^2</mrow>
	  <mrow>\amp = 3\left(x^2 + \left(-\frac{4}{3}\right)x +  \left(-\frac{2}{3}\right)^2 - \left(-\frac{2}{3}\right)^2\right) + 5\amp\amp \text{Factor}</mrow>
	  <mrow>\amp = 3\left(\left(x + \left(-\frac{2}{3}\right)\right)^2 - \frac{4}{9}\right) + 5 \amp\amp \text{Distribute}</mrow>
	  <mrow>\amp = 3\left(x - \frac{2}{3}\right)^2 - \frac{4}{3} + \frac{15}{3} \amp\amp \text{Simplify}</mrow>
	  <mrow>\amp = 3\left(x - \frac{2}{3}\right)^2 + \frac{11}{3}.</mrow>
	</md>
	<p>
	  The vertex of the quadratic function <m>y = 3x^2 -4x + 5</m> is <m>\left(\frac{2}{3}, \frac{11}{3}\right).</m>
	</p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>The Quadratic Equation</title>
    <p>
      A point <m>(x,0)</m> in the Cartesian plane is an <xref ref="def-x_intercept" text="title"/> for the quadratic function <m>y = ax^2 + bx + c</m> if the first coordinate is a solution to the <term>quadratic equation</term>
      <idx>
	<h>Equation</h>
	<h>Quadratic</h>
      </idx>
      <me>0 = ax^2 + bx + c.</me>
      To find the solutions to a quadratic equation, we use the final form from <xref ref="alg-completing_the_square" text="title"/> to rewrite the equation as
      <me>0 = ax^2 + bx + c = a\left(x + \frac{b}{2a}\right)^2 - \frac{b^2 - 4ac}{4a}</me>
      and solve this equation for <m>x</m>
      <md>
	<mrow>0 \amp= a\left(x + \frac{b}{2a}\right)^2 - \frac{b^2 - 4ac}{4a} \amp\amp \text{Add}\ \frac{b^2 - 4ac}{4a}\ \text{to both sides}</mrow>
	<mrow>a\left(x + \frac{b}{2a}\right)^2 \amp= \frac{b^2 - 4ac}{4a} \amp\amp \text{Divide both sides by}\ a</mrow>
	<mrow>\left(x + \frac{b}{2a}\right)^2 \amp= \frac{b^2 - 4ac}{4a^2} \amp\amp \text{Take the square root of both sides}</mrow>
	<mrow>x + \frac{b}{2a} \amp= \pm\sqrt{\frac{b^2 - 4ac}{4a^2}} \amp\amp \text{Simplify}</mrow>
	<mrow>x + \frac{b}{2a} \amp= \pm\frac{\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{\sqrt{4a^2}} \amp\amp \text{Simplify}</mrow>
	<mrow>x + \frac{b}{2a} \amp= \frac{\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a} \amp\amp \text{Subtract}\ \frac{b}{2a}\ \text{from both sides}</mrow>
	<mrow>x \amp= - \frac{b}{2a} + \frac{\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a} \amp\amp \text{Simplify}</mrow>
	<mrow>x \amp= \frac{-b \pm \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a} \amp\amp \text{Simplify}</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

    <p>
      It is important to note that these solutions are real numbers only when <m>b^2 - 4ac</m> is a non-negative number.
      This is an important invariant of a quadratic function.
    </p>
    
    <definition xml:id="def-discriminant">
      <title>The Discriminant</title>
      <p>
	The <term>discriminant</term>
	<idx>
	  <h>Function</h>
	  <h>Quadratic</h>
	  <h>Discriminant</h>
	</idx>
	of the quadratic function <m>y = ax^2 + bx + c</m> is the number
	<me>D = b^2 - 4ac</me>
      </p>
    </definition>

    <p>
      The discriminant provides both algebraic and geometric information about quadratic functions.
      On the algebraic side, the discriminant tells us how many solutions there are to the quadratic equation
      <m>ax^2 + bx  +c = 0</m>.
    </p>
    
    <theorem>
      <title>The Quadratic Formula</title>
      <statement>
	<p>
	  The quadratic equation
	  <me>ax + bx + c = 0</me>
	  has either two, one, or zero real solutions, depending on the <xref ref="def-discriminant" text="title"/>, <m>D = b^2 - 4ac</m>.
	  <ol>
	    <li>
	      <p>
		If <m>D > 0</m>, then the two solutions are
		<me>x = \frac{-b + \sqrt{D}}{2a}
		\quad\text{and}\quad
		x = \frac{-b - \sqrt{D}}{2a}.</me>
	      </p>
	    </li>
	    <li>
	      If <m>D = 0</m>, then the only solution is
	      <me>x = \frac{-b + \sqrt{D}}{2a} = \frac{-b}{2a}.</me>
	    </li>
	    <li>
	      If <m>D \lt 0</m>, then there are no real solutions.
	    </li>
	  </ol>
	</p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p>
      On the geometric side, the discriminant tells us how many <m>x</m>-intercepts the graph of <m>y = ax^2 + bx + c</m> has.
    </p>
    
    <theorem>
      <title>The <m>x</m>-intercepts of a Quadratic Function</title>
      <p>
	The quadratic function <m>y = ax^2 + bx + c</m> has either two, one, or zero <m>x</m>-intercepts, depending on the <xref ref="def-discriminant" text="title"/>, <m>D = b^2 - 4ac</m>.
	<ol>
	  <li>
	    <p>
	      If <m>D > 0</m>, then there are two <m>x</m>-intercepts,
	      <me>\left(\frac{-b + \sqrt{D}}{2a},0\right)
	      \quad\text{and}\quad
	      \left(\frac{-b - \sqrt{D}}{2a},\right).</me>
	    </p>
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    If <m>D = 0</m>, then there is one <m>x</m>-intercept
	    <me>\left(\frac{-b}{2a},0\right).</me>
	    Note this is the vertex.
	  </li>
	  <li>
	    If <m>D \lt 0</m>, then there are no <m>x</m>-intercepts.
	  </li>
	</ol>
      </p>
    </theorem>
  </subsection>
